I now have the full picture. Here is the complete diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

The investigation found **three distinct problems**:

1. **The SCSS is missing the `.solid` modifier class entirely.** `Navigation.tsx` conditionally applies `styles.solid` when `appearance === "solid"`, but `Navigation.module.scss` never defines `.solid`. The component is wired correctly in TypeScript but renders with no visual distinction from `frosted` at runtime.

2. **The playground page already has the `solid` variant documented.** The page at `playground/src/app/components/navigation/page.tsx` has both the `ComponentPreview` block and the correct `PropsTable` entry. So the complaint "you almost never do" is historically accurate — EAP-082 has fired before (ENG-004, ENG-102, ENG-106) — but in *this specific instance* the playground was written ahead of the SCSS, leaving a broken demo that appears to work.

3. **No structural enforcement exists at the component-authoring level.** The guardrail (guardrail-engineering-24 → EAP-082) exists in AGENTS.md, but there is no checklist step *inside the component-authoring workflow* that makes playground parity a blocking pre-condition before the component work is considered done.

---

## Root Cause

**EAP-082 — Adding a Variant/Prop to a DS Component Without Updating the Playground Page.** In this case the failure mode is inverted (playground written, SCSS omitted), but it is the same root gap: variant work was not treated as a single atomic unit covering all three surfaces simultaneously — (1) TypeScript type, (2) SCSS implementation, (3) playground demo. Splitting across surfaces without a checklist guarantees one surface is always missed.

---

## Fix

### 1. Add the missing `.solid` modifier to `Navigation.module.scss`

The `.solid` class needs to override `frosted`'s backdrop blur and make the background fully opaque. Based on the playground's own description ("fully opaque terra-05 background, no blur"), this is the correct addition at the end of `.nav`:

```scss
// src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss

.nav {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: var(--portfolio-z-sticky);
  background-color: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle);
  box-shadow: 0 4px 12px -4px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);

  &::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 0;
    left: 0;
    right: 0;
    height: 10px;
    transform: translateY(100%);
    backdrop-filter: blur(3px);
    -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(3px);
    mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2), transparent);
    -webkit-mask-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2), transparent);
    pointer-events: none;
  }
}

// ── ADD THIS ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
// appearance="solid": fully opaque surface, no blur halo. Use when the nav
// must be a hard visual boundary (e.g., over a plain bg or a colored section).
.solid {
  // The frosted variant achieves translucency via the browser compositing the
  // semi-transparent background over whatever scrolls behind it. Solid locks
  // that surface to full opacity.
  background-color: var(--portfolio-surface-terra-05);
  backdrop-filter: none;
  -webkit-backdrop-filter: none;

  // Kill the blur halo that bleeds below the frosted nav.
  &::after {
    display: none;
  }
}
// ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
```

> **Token note:** The playground page says "fully opaque terra-05" — use `--portfolio-surface-terra-05`. If that token doesn't exist yet (the base `.nav` uses `--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle`), either use `--portfolio-surface-terra-subtle` with an explicit `opacity: 1` override, or confirm the right token. The critical behaviors are: opaque background, `backdrop-filter: none`, and `::after { display: none }` to kill the trailing blur halo.

### 2. The playground page already has correct coverage — no changes needed

`playground/src/app/components/navigation/page.tsx` already contains:
- A `ComponentPreview` titled **"Frosted (default)"** with correct code sample
- A `ComponentPreview` titled **"Solid"** with `appearance="solid"` and accurate description
- A `PropsTable` entry for `appearance` with both union members
- A Notes bullet on the hover/transition behavior

The demo renders the live `@ds/Navigation` component, so once the SCSS fix lands the playground will automatically show the correct visual distinction. No changes to the playground page are needed.

### 3. Codify the rule — add the Variant Completion Checklist to the component-authoring workflow

The structural gap is that variant work has no completion gate. Add the following in two places:

---

**`AGENTS.md`** — extend guardrail-engineering-24 with an explicit checklist:

```markdown
24. <a id="guardrail-engineering-24"></a>**ALWAYS** update the playground page when
    adding a new variant, prop, or visual state to any DS component — the playground
    is the living contract between the design system and its consumers. A variant that
    exists in TypeScript but is absent from the playground does not exist as far as any
    consumer is concerned. See EAP-082.

    **Variant Completion Checklist (all three must be done before the task is closed):**
    - [ ] **Type** — `NavigationAppearance` (or equivalent union/enum) includes the new value
    - [ ] **SCSS** — a `.variantName` modifier class exists in the component's `.module.scss`
          and produces a visually distinct result
    - [ ] **Playground** — `playground/src/app/components/<slug>/page.tsx` has a
          `ComponentPreview` block for the new variant AND the `PropsTable` lists it
          with the correct type, default, and description

    If any of the three is missing, the variant is **incomplete**. Do not mark the
    task done, do not commit, until all three pass. This checklist fires whenever
    the word "variant," "appearance," "size," "state," or "prop" appears in the
    task description for a `src/components/ui/` component.
```

---

**`.cursor/rules/playground-components.md`** — add a mirrored gate at the top of the Non-Negotiable section:

```markdown
## Variant Parity Gate (runs when a NEW variant or prop was just added to a DS component)

When the current task involved adding a variant/prop to `src/components/ui/<Component>`,
run this gate before marking the task done:

1. **SCSS check** — does `<Component>.module.scss` contain a class for each value in the
   TypeScript union? `grep -n '<variantValue>' src/components/ui/<Component>/<Component>.module.scss`
   If the grep returns nothing, the variant has no visual implementation. **Stop. Fix the SCSS.**

2. **Playground check** — does `playground/src/app/components/<slug>/page.tsx` render a
   `<ComponentPreview>` for the new variant?
   `grep -n 'appearance="<variantValue>"' playground/src/app/components/<slug>/page.tsx`
   If the grep returns nothing, the variant is undocumented. **Stop. Add the preview block.**

3. **PropsTable check** — does the `PropsTable` list the updated type string?
   `grep -n '"<variantValue>"' playground/src/app/components/<slug>/page.tsx`

All three must pass. Only then proceed to flush-and-restart.
```

---

**`docs/engineering-anti-patterns.md`** — strengthen EAP-082 with the inverted failure mode now observed:

Find the existing EAP-082 entry and append:

```
Updated [today's date]: A second failure mode observed — playground page written
before the SCSS modifier was added. TypeScript type ✓, playground demo ✓, SCSS
class ✗. The demo renders but produces no visual distinction because `styles.solid`
resolves to `undefined` at runtime. The Variant Completion Checklist in
guardrail-engineering-24 guards both directions: missing playground AND missing SCSS.
```

---

## Principle

**A variant is not a feature until all three surfaces agree: type, style, and documentation.** The TypeScript union is a declaration of intent. The SCSS is the implementation. The playground is the proof. Splitting them across separate tasks — or writing two of three in the same task — makes the gap invisible because each surface appears "done" in isolation. The Variant Completion Checklist (guardrail-engineering-24) treats all three as a single atomic commit, not a sequence of optional steps.

